00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:04.970
Robert Lowell was born

00:04:04.970 --> 00:04:09.710
into a prominent New
England family in 1917.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:13.660
He was a poet of great
originality and huge influence

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:17.590
in American poetry and
Western poetry in general.

00:04:17.590 --> 00:04:22.290
He was twice awarded the Pulitzer
Prize for Poetry and, as Anne said,

00:04:22.290 --> 00:04:26.560
in 1947 and 1948 he was a
Consultant in Poetry here

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:28.400
at the Library of Congress.

00:04:28.400 --> 00:04:32.720
That was the early title for
Poet Laureate of United States.

00:04:32.720 --> 00:04:35.730
Lowell suffered throughout
his life from manic-depressive

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:41.000
or bipolar illness, from a
particularly terrible form of it

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.950
and was hospitalized for
mania nearly 20 times.

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:51.220
He died in 1977, at the age of 60.

00:04:51.220 --> 00:04:54.200
So, I'm gonna talk just for a
little while, for a few minutes

00:04:54.200 --> 00:05:01.460
about Robert Lowell and his poetry,
and then a little bit about some

00:05:01.460 --> 00:05:04.410
of the overlapping similarities

00:05:04.410 --> 00:05:07.610
between Robert Lowell
and Michael Hersch.

00:05:07.610 --> 00:05:09.760
Not the mental illness
side of things,

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:12.890
but the genius side of things.

00:05:12.890 --> 00:05:17.250
And then, Michael and I are
going to talk, not so long,

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:21.140
because we'd like to leave it
open for a lot of questions.

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:25.870
"Darkness honestly lived
through is a place of wonder

00:05:25.870 --> 00:05:28.200
and life," Robert Lowell wrote.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.120
"So much has come from there."

00:05:31.120 --> 00:05:36.020
It was October 1957, and he was
40 years old, writing poetry

00:05:36.020 --> 00:05:40.780
like a house on fire, and taking
darkness into a new country.

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:44.190
It was, he said, the best
writing he had ever done.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:47.620
His new work became the
heart of life studies,

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:52.290
described by one critic as "the
most influential book of poetry

00:05:52.290 --> 00:05:58.770 position:56%
since T.S. Eliot's 'The Waste
Land.'" The poems, most written well

00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:01.980
and in few months time,
left their mark.

00:06:01.980 --> 00:06:05.050
"They have made a conquest,"
wrote The Reviewer.

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:09.310
"They have won a major expansion
of the territory of the poetry."

00:06:09.310 --> 00:06:15.530
In December 1957, after a summer
and fall blaze of writing,

00:06:15.530 --> 00:06:19.640
Lowell was admitted to
psychiatric hospital in Boston.

00:06:19.640 --> 00:06:23.490
He was psychotic, manic, insane.

00:06:23.490 --> 00:06:27.760
It was his fifth psychiatric
hospitalization in 8 years.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:31.130 position:56%
These were long hospitalizations,
not like our modern hospitalizations

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:37.040 position:56%
where people get admitted and leave
almost as soon as they get admitted.

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:39.440
Oh, these were hospitalizations
of many months.

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:42.940
These were severe manias, where he
would be put in straight jacket,

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:49.060
taken in hospital by six or
seven Boston police officers.

00:06:49.060 --> 00:06:51.690
Lowell told the doctor
who admitted him

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:53.740
that the preceding
months had been some

00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:56.550
of the most productive
months of his writing poetry.

00:06:56.550 --> 00:07:01.990 position:56%
It was a pattern he had come to know
well - first the weeks of intense,

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:06.380
fiery writing, then the spike
in the mania, and finally,

00:07:06.380 --> 00:07:11.620
as night follows day, the dusts
in the blood of depression.

00:07:11.620 --> 00:07:15.250
The psychiatrist wrote in
Lowell's medical chart what many

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:17.660
of his doctors were to observe.

00:07:17.660 --> 00:07:22.030
"The patient's had a series
of breaks," she wrote,

00:07:22.030 --> 00:07:25.410
"all in light of unusual
literary output."

00:07:25.410 --> 00:07:32.090
Much had come from the
darkness, but not without a cost.

00:07:32.090 --> 00:07:35.520
Mania and imagination
many times come together

00:07:35.520 --> 00:07:38.490
to help create great art.

00:07:38.490 --> 00:07:44.090
But disciplining character
makes art from inborn gift.

00:07:44.090 --> 00:07:49.130 position:56%
"Poetry may come from a unhappy and
disordered life," Lowell once wrote,

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:53.350
"but a huge amount of health
has to go into the misery."

00:07:53.350 --> 00:07:55.720
Without question, Lowell's attacks

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:59.520
of mania splurged some
of his finest works.

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:03.380
They also brought great pain
to him and to those he loved.

00:08:03.380 --> 00:08:08.260 position:56%
Things he had done, when he was
manic, haunted him when he was well.

00:08:08.260 --> 00:08:11.570
He was mortified and ashamed.

00:08:11.570 --> 00:08:16.350
So too did his terror that he
would become psychotic again.

00:08:16.350 --> 00:08:21.230
Yet, Lowell came back from madness
time and time and time again,

00:08:21.230 --> 00:08:25.540
re-entered the fray and
kept intact his friendships.

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:28.390
He kept his wit, he
kept his capacity

00:08:28.390 --> 00:08:31.080
to love, he went back to work.

00:08:31.080 --> 00:08:37.190 position:56%
This faculty for regeneration is
not a common one, nor is the courage

00:08:37.190 --> 00:08:42.470
to face and to rate from the
certainty of impending madness.

00:08:42.470 --> 00:08:44.650
Courage is unusual.

00:08:44.650 --> 00:08:49.370
So too is creating poetry
that expands the territory.

00:08:49.370 --> 00:08:52.730
Lowell's poetic imagination
was tethered to an unstable,

00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:55.560
but fiercely disciplined mind.

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:59.240
It forged his work and
it branded his life.

00:09:00.510 --> 00:09:02.910
"When I'm dead," Lowell
once told a friend,

00:09:02.910 --> 00:09:05.390
"I don't care what
you write about me.

00:09:05.390 --> 00:09:09.680
All I ask is that it be serious."

00:09:09.680 --> 00:09:13.810
Lowell's seriousness of purpose
was matched by a vaulting ambition,

00:09:13.810 --> 00:09:16.480
that had been his since childhood.

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:21.080
It was a desire and a capacity
for rashness, ambition,

00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:23.710
the great sweep of great ideas.

00:09:23.710 --> 00:09:26.690
It was something he
admired in other writers.

00:09:26.690 --> 00:09:31.510
"Melville and Hawthorne he loved,"
Lowell once wrote, "pour out more

00:09:31.510 --> 00:09:33.340
than the measure will hold.

00:09:33.340 --> 00:09:37.580
What wonderful dangers,
errors, condescensions

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:40.200
and breathless abundance."

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:44.030
Lowell, Hawthorne,
Melville, Whitman --

00:09:44.030 --> 00:09:47.810
all like Coleridge were
habituated to the vast.

00:09:47.810 --> 00:09:50.060
They swung for the fences.

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:53.540
They wrote to change the game.

00:09:53.540 --> 00:09:57.550
Many of Lowell's early poems,
including several of those chosen

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:01.550
as texts for this evening's
music by Michael Hersch,

00:10:01.550 --> 00:10:07.380
are dominated by themes of
moral decay, of pain, suffering,

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:10.230
a fallen New England, retribution,

00:10:10.230 --> 00:10:14.040
and the unforgiving
puritanism of his ancestors.

00:10:14.040 --> 00:10:17.230
He wrote of the complex
burden of heritage

00:10:17.230 --> 00:10:21.130
and of the dark, ambiguous
grace of God.

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:25.910
The battle that raged between
Calvinism, his native tongue,

00:10:25.910 --> 00:10:29.160
the New England protestantism
that he had known longest

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:33.190
and breathed most deeply, and
the catholicism that he had

00:10:33.190 --> 00:10:37.310
as an adult taken to heart
and mind, and then quit,

00:10:37.310 --> 00:10:41.190
was one that was reflected
in part in his mental wars.

00:10:41.190 --> 00:10:46.080 position:56%
It was a clash that entered into his
work violently and unforgettably,

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:51.380
in his early poems, work that
the most influential critic

00:10:51.380 --> 00:10:57.970
of the time said would be read
as long as men remember English.

00:10:57.970 --> 00:11:04.030
These were poems of ambition, elegy
and blood, coiled and unstable

00:11:04.030 --> 00:11:08.480
in force and fury, and
crafted with brilliance.

00:11:08.480 --> 00:11:13.080
Lowell's great poem "The
Quaker Graveyard in Nantucket,"

00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:18.150
which Michael Hersh has drawn
from this evening, in part,

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:24.380
was a debt to Melville and The Old
Testament, to Thoreau, to Hopkins.

00:11:24.380 --> 00:11:29.230
It is Homeric in force, mythic in
scale and spelled by the violence

00:11:29.230 --> 00:11:33.580
of God in Lowell's home
North Atlantic waters.

00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:35.860
It is the battleground
for the contrasting forces

00:11:35.860 --> 00:11:39.140
that defined his mind
as a young poet.

00:11:39.140 --> 00:11:44.310
The poem, as Seamus Heaney said,
is one where "the percussion

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:48.590
and brass section of the
language orchestra is driven hard"

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:52.290
and "the string section
hardly gets a look-in."

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:58.930
Michael Hersch has essential things
in common with Robert Lowell.

00:11:58.930 --> 00:12:02.460
He's an unrelenting
way serious artist.

00:12:02.460 --> 00:12:07.050
His work is rooted in a profound
knowledge of grief and death

00:12:07.050 --> 00:12:13.370
and life of the human condition,
in art, literature and in music.

00:12:13.370 --> 00:12:18.670
He has, like Lowell, a
restless, tectonic imagination

00:12:18.670 --> 00:12:21.080
and the courage of his beliefs.

00:12:21.080 --> 00:12:23.450
He takes risks.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.780 position:56%
Lowell, it is always said, and there
is somebody who is writing a book

00:12:27.780 --> 00:12:30.450
about him, it is the first thing
if anybody has actually heard

00:12:30.450 --> 00:12:32.950
of Lowell, the first
thing that people say is,

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:35.410
"He is a really difficult poet."

00:12:35.410 --> 00:12:37.220
Lowell is a difficult poet.

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:40.300
It's part of what makes him great.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:44.330
So too is Michael a
difficult composer.

00:12:44.330 --> 00:12:48.780
His work is complex,
unpredictable, dark, and wonderful.

00:12:48.780 --> 00:12:51.450
It is beautiful.

00:12:51.450 --> 00:12:53.660
It is piercingly human.

00:12:53.660 --> 00:12:57.510
And I am honored to be
here with him tonight.

