00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:51.840
It's incredibly specific to me and
there is oftentimes no real method

00:16:51.840 --> 00:17:01.030
or obvious methodology to how
I'm engaging with these texts.

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:04.250
So that was really notable
and, in Lowell's case,

00:17:04.250 --> 00:17:12.170
that terrain of the expression
that I was feeling myself,

00:17:12.170 --> 00:17:17.910 position:56%
looking for companionship and
certain text fragments came to mind.

00:17:17.910 --> 00:17:22.530
So, when I was writing this music,
I started the music before I went

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:30.110
to the Lowell, but certain text
fragments of Lowell came to mind.

00:17:30.110 --> 00:17:35.000 position:56%
Maybe one of the first was a line in
poem; it's just something as simple

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:39.140
as "Canaries beat their
bars and scream",

00:17:39.140 --> 00:17:43.190
and that just popped into my mind.

00:17:43.190 --> 00:17:47.140
Or, another image of two
angels fighting over the soul

00:17:47.140 --> 00:17:48.440
of the man with billhooks.

00:17:48.440 --> 00:17:57.110
These kinds of images that were
just incredibly searing images

00:17:57.110 --> 00:17:59.300
and I would just be writing and
then they would come to mind

00:17:59.300 --> 00:18:05.620 position:56%
and then I would go and try to track
down where did I remember that from?

00:18:05.620 --> 00:18:10.880
And sometimes there would be
musical allusions to leave talk --

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:14.850
there is a rhyme where he talks
about hell being burned out

00:18:14.850 --> 00:18:18.310
and heaven's harps-strings
going slack.

00:18:18.310 --> 00:18:24.550
And then somehow these all start
to tie together, to tailor together

00:18:24.550 --> 00:18:29.640
and ultimately it makes sense -
they were from the same collection.

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:33.800
But that surprised me, because
usually people are trying

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:35.960
to make sense of what
the relationships are

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:37.660
between different text fragments.

00:18:37.660 --> 00:18:41.100
But in this case it was
very clean that way.

00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:47.370
But that just speaks to the
consistency of rendering

00:18:47.370 --> 00:18:49.500 position:56%
of his own imagination at that time.

00:18:49.500 --> 00:18:50.800
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Right,

00:18:50.800 --> 00:18:55.270
anything that would have exist
very clear and fascinating

00:18:55.270 --> 00:18:58.660
about Lowell is he's one of these
writers, rather like Beethoven,

00:18:58.660 --> 00:19:00.240
who just moved from effort.

00:19:00.240 --> 00:19:06.780
He just moved and changed
and went on and recreated,

00:19:06.780 --> 00:19:13.770
and so that Lord Weary's Castle,
which is made of mostly fragments,

00:19:13.770 --> 00:19:22.500
is completely different from so
much of the work he did after that.

00:19:22.500 --> 00:19:26.750
So, very, very different.

00:19:26.750 --> 00:19:32.130 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Yes, and
there's no real explanation as to --

00:19:32.130 --> 00:19:35.750
the interesting thing -- really,
it's not so interesting --

00:19:35.750 --> 00:19:43.060
is that I'm not looking for
something that is trying

00:19:43.060 --> 00:19:48.280
to capture a sort of
emotional or psychological --

00:19:48.280 --> 00:19:51.090
there's something that's
going to click

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:53.120
with a feeling, with that feeling.

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:55.640
I'm not after an image
and I think that's one

00:19:55.640 --> 00:20:00.280
of the complicating factors
in a piece like this.

00:20:00.280 --> 00:20:04.440
I'm certainly not the first person
to engage with text this way,

00:20:04.440 --> 00:20:08.660
but a lot of times
people like the idea.

00:20:08.660 --> 00:20:13.510
It's a very clean idea to take
an image that's laid out in words

00:20:13.510 --> 00:20:16.530
that we all understand and then
the idea of composer taking that

00:20:16.530 --> 00:20:20.990
and trying to render that or
transform that into sound.

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:22.850
That's too fastle.

00:20:22.850 --> 00:20:25.770
I don't know if that's
the right use of the word.

00:20:25.770 --> 00:20:28.650
It's more nuance than that.

00:20:28.650 --> 00:20:36.310
These images are a byproduct
of something that's a feeling,

00:20:36.310 --> 00:20:39.600
a state of mind, a state of being.

00:20:39.600 --> 00:20:43.030 position:56%
I think that one of the things
that's extraordinary about Lowell is

00:20:43.030 --> 00:20:45.460
that he's able to take
something as simple as an image,

00:20:45.460 --> 00:20:46.760
though, and capture that.

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:50.550
That's a very hard thing to do.

00:20:50.550 --> 00:20:54.750
I found that for me, what was
different about these texts

00:20:54.750 --> 00:20:59.720
versus others is how visual they
are, or to me they are visual.

00:20:59.720 --> 00:21:03.750
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: He
described capturing experience

00:21:03.750 --> 00:21:07.830
in talks, you know, and
you would look at them.

00:21:07.830 --> 00:21:13.600
I think one of his famous
images was meat-hooked --

00:21:13.600 --> 00:21:16.010
words "meat-hooked
from the living steer."

00:21:16.010 --> 00:21:20.530
I mean, it's that incredibly
graphic imagery that, you know,

00:21:20.530 --> 00:21:25.740
you have to have a heart of stone
to remain unresponsive to, I think.

00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:27.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Yeah, yeah.

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:28.340
No, I --

00:21:28.340 --> 00:21:29.840
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison:
Do you see anything kind

00:21:29.840 --> 00:21:33.030
of intrinsically musical
about Lowell's work?

00:21:33.030 --> 00:21:37.890
I mean, by definition poetry is
musical, but is there anything

00:21:37.890 --> 00:21:41.180
that sets him apart in that?

00:21:41.180 --> 00:21:49.140
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: You know, for
me what's interesting is most

00:21:49.140 --> 00:21:54.580
