of English and the admiration

00:22:12.650 --> 00:22:14.120
that I have and the
gratitude that I have

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:18.270
for great translators
can't be overstated.

00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:21.350
Of course, Lowell translated
as well.

00:22:21.350 --> 00:22:23.640
So, what was interesting was along

00:22:23.640 --> 00:22:26.370
with just a few other people
here was some writing in English.

00:22:26.370 --> 00:22:28.810
So there's just something
inherently musical to me

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:36.780
about seeing these thoughts, these
feelings, these recollections,

00:22:36.780 --> 00:22:39.410
these terrors, these premonitions,

00:22:39.410 --> 00:22:43.920
whatever you might
call them, in English.

00:22:43.920 --> 00:22:47.490
They were originally
conceived in English and,

00:22:47.490 --> 00:22:48.890
because that's my language,

00:22:48.890 --> 00:22:51.190
that's the language I'm
most comfortable with,

00:22:51.190 --> 00:22:53.560
there's something inherently
musical to me.

00:22:53.560 --> 00:22:57.790
That's not answering your
question exactly, but yes,

00:22:57.790 --> 00:23:00.210
I do find there's something
particularly musical

00:23:00.210 --> 00:23:04.850
about these words and the way
that they are laid out on page.

00:23:04.850 --> 00:23:08.850
But, of course, in this case I'm
not setting any of these words.

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:14.180
I just told someone earlier
that I've written a lot of music

00:23:14.180 --> 00:23:18.580
that has relationships with
text in one way or another.

00:23:18.580 --> 00:23:21.690
Just like this piece -
