00:26:23.420 --> 00:26:34.630 position:56%
that's always a bit tempestuous and
on some level I was puzzled by this.

00:26:34.630 --> 00:26:42.020
But what's interesting is that for
him that was his life, at the time.

00:26:42.020 --> 00:26:45.190
For me, life -- for all
of us as we get older --

00:26:45.190 --> 00:26:50.400
becomes defined more and
more by advance and actions

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:53.470
and things that have boundaries.

00:26:53.470 --> 00:26:56.210
Sometimes these boundaries
become unclear

00:26:56.210 --> 00:26:58.410
or broken and then they spill.

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:01.640
But it was interesting how
something that very clearly

00:27:01.640 --> 00:27:07.740 position:56%
for him was all-encompassing, a sort
of his state of mind over a period

00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:13.410
of years, applied so nicely
to something where I was put

00:27:13.410 --> 00:27:17.220
in this state of mind of
something very specific

00:27:17.220 --> 00:27:25.650
that does recapture the sort of
generic trauma of being younger.

00:27:25.650 --> 00:27:31.580
In this case it was real traumas
and so I was able to take something

00:27:31.580 --> 00:27:35.260
that on the surface didn't
seem to match so much

00:27:35.260 --> 00:27:36.560
with where I was in my life.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:41.130
But then taken and put inside,
encapsulated in a series of events

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:43.930
in my life, it actually
worked really nicely.

00:27:43.930 --> 00:27:46.170
I'm only thinking about
this right now,

00:27:46.170 --> 00:27:50.890
I haven't actually thought
too much about that.

00:27:50.890 --> 00:27:55.630 position:56%
So, in that sense, the period in his
life is not really relevant to me.

00:27:55.630 --> 00:27:59.220
Many artists have done a lot
of great things at that period,

00:27:59.220 --> 00:28:03.300
it's not such an extraordinary
age to do the work.

00:28:03.300 --> 00:28:07.770
But there's a totality to
his state of mind and a sort

00:28:07.770 --> 00:28:13.230
of all-encompassing-ness to that
state of mind that he's able

00:28:13.230 --> 00:28:16.630
to sustain without seeming like --

00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:23.990
he's able to avoid these traps that
lot of people, when we're younger,

00:28:23.990 --> 00:28:33.560
fall into - self-pity or
just sort of undefined angst.

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:38.240
It just translates so nicely to
real world of grown up things

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:44.240
that are defined in advance,
and in that sense it's

00:28:44.240 --> 00:28:48.420
that mature level that's
quite extraordinary, I think.

00:28:48.420 --> 00:28:51.700
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Gee, can
you write a chapter for my book?

00:28:51.700 --> 00:28:53.830
That's very good.

00:28:53.830 --> 00:28:55.170
That's very true.

00:28:55.170 --> 00:28:57.080
I think too, with Lowell,
as you say,

00:28:57.080 --> 00:29:04.200
he was 29 when he got Pulitzer
Prize for his body of work.

00:29:04.200 --> 00:29:07.340
By that time he had been

00:29:07.340 --> 00:29:11.830
through just an incredible
series of life-times.

00:29:11.830 --> 00:29:17.290 position:56%
I think partly he was born
tempestuous and he died tempestuous,

00:29:17.290 --> 00:29:20.990
but this was a period of
time that was just striking

00:29:20.990 --> 00:29:25.180
for the changes in
his emotional being.

00:29:25.180 --> 00:29:28.410
And then in just a few years time
that he would be hospitalized

00:29:28.410 --> 00:29:30.350
for the first time for mania.

00:29:30.350 --> 00:29:34.390
But you can feel the mania
in the work and certainly

00:29:34.390 --> 00:29:36.710
in the lines of the works.

00:29:36.710 --> 00:29:41.670
I think what's also interesting
is that, not unlike many people,

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:45.880
of course, he had great love for
music and he wrote about music.

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:48.700
So he wrote a sonnet
about [inaudible],

00:29:48.700 --> 00:29:53.120
a sonnet about the Archduke trio
that's being played tonight.

00:29:53.120 --> 00:29:55.870
He wrote sonnets about
Beethoven, Schubert,

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:59.460
the two great composers
that he most loved.

00:29:59.460 --> 00:30:01.710
There was something always
in the back of his mind

00:30:01.710 --> 00:30:05.360
that you had the sense
was being formed by music,

00:30:05.360 --> 00:30:09.640
his being classicist by
education and training and heart.

00:30:09.640 --> 00:30:12.610
By other poets, by
other writers, by love.

00:30:12.610 --> 00:30:16.060
I mean, this is hugely
broad and not this kind

00:30:16.060 --> 00:30:19.260
of picky or manicured life that -

00:30:19.260 --> 00:30:22.230
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: You know, he
seemed to me looked around him

00:30:22.230 --> 00:30:24.210
and he had that sense, you know.

00:30:24.210 --> 00:30:27.510
And, you know, and
it's - I knew the --

00:30:27.510 --> 00:30:32.160
for me, you know, I feel
that all the early years

00:30:32.160 --> 00:30:37.430
that I was composing, certainly
through my late teens and 20s,

00:30:37.430 --> 00:30:44.700
I didn't feel like I had
my head above the clouds,

00:30:44.700 --> 00:30:48.380
until I got on the far side of 25.

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:52.190
I just feel like there was
so much I just wasn't seeing

00:30:52.190 --> 00:30:57.350
and for me it took some time.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:31:02.470
It took me into, such
as read something

00:31:02.470 --> 00:31:06.180
where someone had this sort
of control of his materials

00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:09.570
and had a sense of
what was around them.

00:31:09.570 --> 00:31:12.940
I don't mean sense of
influence, I mean just a sense

00:31:12.940 --> 00:31:18.050
of the human landscape
that surrounded him.

00:31:18.050 --> 00:31:23.840
I feel like I'm still
noticing things.

00:31:23.840 --> 00:31:27.480
We all of us are going to
notice things hopefully always,

00:31:27.480 --> 00:31:32.560
but what was interesting just
looking back from that perspective,

00:31:32.560 --> 00:31:36.280
to be able to see someone
who had figured that out

00:31:36.280 --> 00:31:39.730
and there was a clarity of
thought in a relatively young age.

00:31:39.730 --> 00:31:42.140
Well, I was sure that I had
that clarity of thought then,

00:31:42.140 --> 00:31:46.880
but it's interesting and a lot
of times I've found that writers

00:31:46.880 --> 00:31:51.200
and poets have that clarity
of thought before musicians.

00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:52.920
I don't know why that may be.

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:56.830
I don't know if I have any clarity
of thought yet, but there's sense

00:31:56.830 --> 00:32:01.410
of one's self changes and the
sense of being in the dark.

00:32:01.410 --> 00:32:07.630
But he just had this sort of
omniscience that comes through.

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:10.820
Whether it was real or not, it is a
sort of force of personality also.

00:32:10.820 --> 00:32:15.920
And I think that's also one of
things that characterizes him -

00:32:15.920 --> 00:32:18.260
the force of his personality
just comes

00:32:18.260 --> 00:32:23.310
through very strongly
from very early on.

00:32:23.310 --> 00:32:27.310
And that's a rare thing.

00:32:27.310 --> 00:32:32.890
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: You see,
