it is for people to really know.

00:34:33.520 --> 00:34:38.850
It's like looking at the wiring
or the piping of the building.

00:34:38.850 --> 00:34:43.950
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Maybe
a little bit more than that.

00:34:43.950 --> 00:34:47.970
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: How does that
reiterate what I've said before?

00:34:47.970 --> 00:34:51.170
That more than any other piece
that I've written that is engaged

00:34:51.170 --> 00:34:56.760
with text, where the
text is not song.

00:34:56.760 --> 00:34:59.250
It's essential to this piece.

00:34:59.250 --> 00:35:03.700
This piece wouldn't have been
written had I not been engaging

00:35:03.700 --> 00:35:05.080
with these texts.

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:10.600
As I said before, the fact that
so many of them just came to mind

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:16.790 position:56%
in an involuntary sort of way speaks
to how important they were to me,

00:35:16.790 --> 00:35:21.210
or have been, maybe
without even knowing it.

00:35:21.210 --> 00:35:26.450
So, even on some level it
may even be OK to refer

00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:30.130
to these center pieces as a
kind of songs without words.

00:35:30.130 --> 00:35:37.380
Except that the words are there,
but they're just not song.

00:35:37.380 --> 00:35:39.650
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Thank you.

00:35:39.650 --> 00:35:41.950
Just open up for questions?

00:35:43.620 --> 00:35:44.920
Yes?

00:35:44.920 --> 00:35:47.730
&gt;&gt; What prompted this
particular choice of pieces?

00:35:47.730 --> 00:35:49.030
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch:
That was just simply

00:35:49.030 --> 00:35:52.550
when the Library approached me.

00:35:52.550 --> 00:35:57.600
They wanted something
that had featured cello,

00:35:57.600 --> 00:36:00.180
so normal thing would
probably be to do a sonata

00:36:00.180 --> 00:36:02.980
for piano or maybe a solo cello.

00:36:02.980 --> 00:36:07.320
But after thinking about that -- I
had to think about it for a while,

00:36:07.320 --> 00:36:11.290
and if I hadnt, you know, even

00:36:11.290 --> 00:36:15.400
with this incredibly generous
opportunity, exciting opportunity,

00:36:15.400 --> 00:36:20.940
I still needed to feel - I have
to feel excited about if I'm going

00:36:20.940 --> 00:36:24.290
to undertake any kind of project.

00:36:24.290 --> 00:36:28.090
At a bare minimum, I have to be
excited about the possibility

00:36:28.090 --> 00:36:32.240
of writing for whatever
the medium is.

00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:33.830
And so I went to them and I said

00:36:33.830 --> 00:36:38.120
that it would be a bit unorthodox
perhaps, but would they allow me

00:36:38.120 --> 00:36:42.470
to write something for violin
and cello, so they said, "yes."

00:36:42.470 --> 00:36:47.760
So that's all.

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:51.470
&gt;&gt; What did Lowell die of --
what did Lowell die of again?

00:36:51.470 --> 00:36:55.260
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: She wants to
know what he died -- how he died.

00:36:55.260 --> 00:36:58.510
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: This is
the composer's daughter, Abby.

00:36:58.510 --> 00:37:00.220
Abby Hersch.

00:37:00.220 --> 00:37:03.510
We're delighted you're here.

00:37:03.510 --> 00:37:10.400 position:56%
Mr. Lowell died of a lot things, but
I would actually turn to my husband,

00:37:10.400 --> 00:37:12.580
who's a cardiologist and
who's doing that side

00:37:12.580 --> 00:37:15.660
of the work, but he died of?

00:37:15.660 --> 00:37:20.000
&gt;&gt; He died of a heart attack.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:21.300
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Yes.

00:37:21.300 --> 00:37:24.800
After years of 4-5 packs
a day of cigarettes,

00:37:24.800 --> 00:37:29.300
not inconsiderable amount
of drinking, and mania,

00:37:29.300 --> 00:37:33.830
which actually elevated
rate for heart disease.

00:37:33.830 --> 00:37:39.710
So he was under intense stress,
so it was a culmination of things.

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:43.080
And both of his parents had
heart disease, so he was living

00:37:43.080 --> 00:37:47.810
under shadows of disease.

00:37:47.810 --> 00:37:49.340
Great question.

00:37:49.340 --> 00:38:03.640
&gt;&gt; Hi, I'm trying to see if I can
put this into words, my question,

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:09.010
but as Dr. Jamison said,
Lowell was very difficult,

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:11.650
just reading this here.

00:38:11.650 --> 00:38:18.380
And it seems more -- what
struck me about it is

00:38:18.380 --> 00:38:24.250
that it's more a collection of
impressions than it does draw

00:38:24.250 --> 00:38:27.770
on a single visual
descriptive kind of thing.

00:38:27.770 --> 00:38:35.610
So if it is a collection
of impressions, I wonder,

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:44.910
in reading this it would call
to mind either ideas or images,

00:38:44.910 --> 00:38:54.070
and which of them will help me
to better understand the music?

00:38:54.070 --> 00:38:57.240
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch:
If it's the music --

00:38:57.240 --> 00:39:00.430
if I've succeeded in any way in
writing what I hoped to write,

00:39:00.430 --> 00:39:02.650
then you hopefully won't need help,

00:39:02.650 --> 00:39:10.330
there shouldn't be anything
referential that you have to do.

00:39:10.330 --> 00:39:16.080
So, when I say it's good
to have those texts there,

00:39:16.080 --> 00:39:18.060
it's like having a passing glance.

00:39:18.060 --> 00:39:20.850
You can read them all at once
and not look at them again,

00:39:20.850 --> 00:39:25.210
you can read -- usually I'm
antagonistic towards the idea

00:39:25.210 --> 00:39:30.410
of reading and listening: I
think listening requires all

00:39:30.410 --> 00:39:38.200
of our faculties and any
distraction is not a good thing.

00:39:38.200 --> 00:39:42.920
So, I guess my expectation would
just be that if you listen to it

00:39:42.920 --> 00:39:46.250
and you have a certain
reactions and you read the text,

00:39:46.250 --> 00:39:50.970
you might just kind of, say
-- you would just sort of nod,

00:39:50.970 --> 00:40:00.080
there would be some sense that
there was a rightness to it.

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:03.840
And if there wasn't, that
can be expected, too.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:08.090
But, again, I just want
to reiterate that I hope

00:40:08.090 --> 00:40:10.920
that the music doesn't
need the poetry.

00:40:10.920 --> 00:40:14.300
I know that those texts
don't need my music.

00:40:14.300 --> 00:40:15.600
That's for sure.

00:40:15.600 --> 00:40:20.300 position:56%
I just think that the presence of
those texts, perhaps, might heighten

00:40:20.300 --> 00:40:24.020
or augment the experience
of listening to music

00:40:24.020 --> 00:40:28.840
through their proximity -
meaning them being on the tip

00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:30.280
of your mind if you read.

00:40:30.280 --> 00:40:37.670
You might just recognize
something of each and in each pole,

00:40:37.670 --> 00:40:39.880
the literary or the
poetical or the music,

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:42.860
that there's some common
ground there.

00:40:42.860 --> 00:40:49.560
I think, frankly, for people who
don't have a lot of experience

00:40:49.560 --> 00:40:53.420
with musical expression
that's beyond, say,

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:58.640
the standard repertoire, it
provides a way in, for some people.

00:40:58.640 --> 00:41:02.780
They're hearing sounds that
they've never heard before

00:41:02.780 --> 00:41:06.720
that and that can be jarring.

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:10.000
So the words can act
as a sort of bridge.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.210
I doubt there is anybody
who can read those texts

00:41:13.210 --> 00:41:16.680
and not have an informed
feeling about it.

00:41:16.680 --> 00:41:18.360
For as the music, people
might listen and say,

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:21.350
"I'm not sure what I've heard."

00:41:21.350 --> 00:41:24.590
Everybody's experiences are
so different with music,

00:41:24.590 --> 00:41:27.600
but our experience with
language is pretty uniform.

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:31.800
And our experience with
music is uniform, too,

00:41:31.800 --> 00:41:37.080
but every composer is
speaking in different languages

00:41:37.080 --> 00:41:39.540
and if you have no
experience with the language,

00:41:39.540 --> 00:41:43.300 position:56%
it's probably not a bad idea to
ground oneself into it a little bit.

00:41:43.300 --> 00:41:45.810
It doesn't mean that you
have to be liking it.

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:51.260 position:56%
But, you see, I'm quite inarticulate
about these relationships with --

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:56.090
because I have never
been asked before.

00:41:56.090 --> 00:42:00.740
So, it's okay to read
those texts, though.

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:02.040
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison:
You might say

00:42:02.040 --> 00:42:07.800
that there is a certain dark thread
that runs through these texts?

00:42:07.800 --> 00:42:11.280
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: I would say
that the thread that I perceive

00:42:11.280 --> 00:42:15.480
through those texts, that is
shared with the music, certainly.

00:42:15.480 --> 00:42:18.820
Mainly what we're dealing
with are issues of loss,

00:42:18.820 --> 00:42:23.500
grief and their appending
in the tentacles.

00:42:23.500 --> 00:42:27.320 position:56%
So, yes, those are the broad strokes

00:42:27.320 --> 00:42:33.390
of expressive territory
that they share.

00:42:33.390 --> 00:42:36.230
Again, whether I succeed
in communicating

00:42:36.230 --> 00:42:38.400
that is certainly an
open-ended question,

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:43.110
but from my standpoint
those were the things

00:42:43.110 --> 00:42:45.660
that I was trying to express.

00:42:45.660 --> 00:42:49.120
And it seems to me
that Lowell was too.

00:42:49.120 --> 00:42:52.740
But I'm also well aware that the
context of a lot of those poems -

00:42:52.740 --> 00:42:57.900
that if you read them in
context, what you take away

00:42:57.900 --> 00:43:00.630
from these fragments would
probably be unrecognizable.

00:43:00.630 --> 00:43:04.440
So, that's a whole another thing,
which is a whole another issue,

00:43:04.440 --> 00:43:09.870
which is for another day - whether
if it's even right for a person

00:43:09.870 --> 00:43:12.270
to extract things like this.

00:43:12.270 --> 00:43:14.360 position:56%
To take these things out of context.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:19.390
I imagine there are a lot of
people who have a real problem

00:43:19.390 --> 00:43:25.640
with one artist, with a composer
taking fragments of a poem

00:43:25.640 --> 00:43:30.550
which was clearly intended
to be read in it's entirety.

00:43:30.550 --> 00:43:33.240
But, that's a risk out there.

00:43:33.240 --> 00:43:36.060
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Well,
apparently Lowell would not be one

00:43:36.060 --> 00:43:39.800
of those, because he actually
was a great translator

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:43.030
to many perspective, but
he got huge criticism.

00:43:43.030 --> 00:43:47.450
He took poems in languages
he didn't know,

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:51.420
took texts from different
language to translate from,

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:53.860
and then wrote his own poetry.

00:43:53.860 --> 00:43:59.570 position:56%
He saw language as living and he saw
language as - you contributed to it.

00:43:59.570 --> 00:44:01.690
And he would be the
first, I think, to say --

00:44:01.690 --> 00:44:03.380
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Okay,
good, all's good to that.

00:44:03.380 --> 00:44:04.680
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Yes.

00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:12.180
And he actually -- Benjamin Britton
wrote music based on Lowell's work

00:44:12.180 --> 00:44:14.710
and he said it was one of the
greatest honors of his life.

00:44:14.710 --> 00:44:18.450
Hhe liked the idea of
being written from.

00:44:25.620 --> 00:44:28.770
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: That's good.

00:44:28.770 --> 00:44:32.120
&gt;&gt; Michael, can you just say
something about the interplay

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:35.380
between the text in your
composition, as to say --

00:44:35.380 --> 00:44:40.120
I understand that you read,
there's impressions that you take,

00:44:40.120 --> 00:44:43.240
there's parts of the poems
that moved you and then

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:49.730
that inspires composition, but are
you composing, re-reading, refining

00:44:49.730 --> 00:44:53.190
or -- can you say something
about your own creative process

00:44:53.190 --> 00:44:56.410
in the interplay between
text and composition?

00:44:56.410 --> 00:45:00.140
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Yes, now that's
the part that is a bit puzzling.

00:45:00.140 --> 00:45:06.190
It's actually -- I'll be writing
and then the words come to mind.

00:45:06.190 --> 00:45:09.660
So, something I do
reminds me of something

00:45:09.660 --> 00:45:12.240
that Lowell did, in this case.

00:45:12.240 --> 00:45:15.370
Then that acts as accelerator,
somehow.

00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:19.250
Like it then feeds whatever
it was that I was --

00:45:19.250 --> 00:45:25.590
so, that's the part that's
a little backwards, I think.

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:30.420
Maybe more at expected
circumstances, where it is a sort

00:45:30.420 --> 00:45:35.550
of you start with the
non-musical object

00:45:35.550 --> 00:45:38.880
that then inspires
something in the composer.

00:45:38.880 --> 00:45:41.660
The composer then -- so, that's
all something like Pictures

00:45:41.660 --> 00:45:46.020
at an Exhibition of Mussorgsky,
that sort of basic idea, right?

00:45:46.020 --> 00:45:49.370
He's capturing these
paintings in music.

00:45:49.370 --> 00:45:54.990
In this case the process comes
from writing and then some

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:59.960
of these text writings
pop into mind.

00:45:59.960 --> 00:46:03.150
If that happens, that's
very meaningful to me,

00:46:03.150 --> 00:46:06.500
because there was no reason for me
to be thinking about these at all.

00:46:06.500 --> 00:46:10.240
I'm into writing this piece, not
thinking about Lowell at all,

00:46:10.240 --> 00:46:17.700 position:56%
but from the outside, somehow, these
text fragments start to come to mind

00:46:17.700 --> 00:46:20.800
and then I have to go
back and find them.

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:23.840
I stay true to what occurred to me,

00:46:23.840 --> 00:46:29.420
that's why they are what they
exactly need to be for me.

00:46:29.420 --> 00:46:34.830
So, sometimes all I need
is one word, it's a back

00:46:34.830 --> 00:46:38.940
and forth in real time, sort of.

00:46:38.940 --> 00:46:44.270
But once I've identified the
text, then that is exciting.

00:46:44.270 --> 00:46:48.830
Then that feeds more, then
I'm getting more from that

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:52.090
and it might oscillate
back and forth.

00:46:52.090 --> 00:47:00.380
So, it really is exciting, because
it's having this living dialogue.

00:47:00.380 --> 00:47:03.460
He's not there, I'm
not talking to him,

00:47:03.460 --> 00:47:08.700
but through his work it
really does feel very much

00:47:08.700 --> 00:47:13.780
like collaboration,
in a strange way.

00:47:13.780 --> 00:47:19.950
&gt;&gt; Lowell was glad to advise
that himself and allow images

00:47:19.950 --> 00:47:22.940
to coagulate, so to speak?

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:24.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Kay Redfield Jamison: Absolutely.

00:47:24.240 --> 00:47:25.540
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Yes.

00:47:25.540 --> 00:47:30.040
&gt;&gt; There is one thing in the
program that's interesting,

00:47:30.040 --> 00:47:38.160
they mentioned quarter tones and it
seems like in the second movement,

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:41.550
which also has the
word Purgatory in it,

00:47:41.550 --> 00:47:44.500
maybe even suggesting
some sort of threshold.

00:47:44.500 --> 00:47:50.270
Is that the only place with quarter
tones and although you're speaking

00:47:50.270 --> 00:47:53.560
in the music, would you want
to say anything about that?

00:47:53.560 --> 00:47:58.040
&gt;&gt; Michael Hersch: Yes, that is one
of the only places that I have --

00:47:58.040 --> 00:48:03.530
there was no conscious one-to-one
correspondence between the idea

00:48:03.530 --> 00:48:14.180
of Purgatory, but where the
quarter tones do appear,

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:19.110
they are very frequent in
the piece and I just think

00:48:19.110 --> 00:48:24.760
of the quarter tone, it's
just another shade of harmony.

00:48:24.760 --> 00:48:28.080
So, it doesn't have
any specific meaning.

00:48:28.080 --> 00:48:30.660
Also, just for the
record, Purgatory --

00:48:30.660 --> 00:48:35.600
I just did a song dealing with
a lot of text on Purgatory

00:48:35.600 --> 00:48:39.520
with texts of Pound and Dante.

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:43.480
It's just interesting, for whatever
reason - when I was younger,

00:48:43.480 --> 00:48:45.970
a number of the texts
that I initially read

00:48:45.970 --> 00:48:52.980
of Dante really presented Purgatory
in a relatively beautiful and sort

00:48:52.980 --> 00:48:56.070
of tranquil, sort of
at ease, in at ease.

00:48:56.070 --> 00:48:59.590
That doesn't mean there's not
a sort of darkness hovering

00:48:59.590 --> 00:49:01.730
around these things, but it's
interesting that in a lot

00:49:01.730 --> 00:49:07.600
of Purgatory, a lot of writing
about it, the way we use it

00:49:07.600 --> 00:49:11.780
in our common parlance
is much more grim than --

00:49:11.780 --> 00:49:16.930
at least in my reading of
Dante or specific parts of it.

00:49:16.930 --> 00:49:20.640
So it's very -- since
you bring up that word,

00:49:20.640 --> 00:49:23.290
it's a very complicated
word, I mean, for me.

00:49:23.290 --> 00:49:27.510
I mean, it has alot --
it's imbued with all kinds

00:49:27.510 --> 00:49:32.950
of complexities and contradictions.

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:35.590
Anyway, but still, the
quarter tones are just

00:49:35.590 --> 00:49:37.810
because that's what the
harmony needed in that spot.

00:49:37.810 --> 00:49:40.420
Anything else?

00:49:40.420 --> 00:49:45.270
No? Well, thank you very much.

00:49:45.270 --> 00:49:47.220
It was a -- thank you.

